Sec 2
	mu-graph is a hierachical graph; at each level, the computation is
represented as a graph, and each node of the graph is a finer level
computation which can also be represented by a lower level graph. A mu-graph in
Mirage has three levels:
		kernel graph, where each node is a kernel
		block graph, where each node is computation done in a thread block
		thread graph, where each node a computation done in a single thread
(does it matter to assume it's for a warp, since instructions are scheduled
this way?)

	Overall, mu-graph works on an abstract level of computation; it relies on
the abstract model shown in figure 2. not many details are architecture
specific. It also is limited to optimizing DNN computations, which is why
treating all data as tensors suffices here.

	There are also a few other compromises the mu-graph made which weren't
explicitly emphasized. The I/O map, in particular, only allow a few modes: 1)
for input, split and replica; 2) for output, concatenation. These obviously
can't cover all operations, e.g. overlapping shift for input (for-loop seems to
partially enable this), or merge for output. But I suppose they may be enough
to cover many while drastically reduce the search space. Such crude compromises
can be good for the specific use case of optimizing tensor programs, but might
not work for more general computations on GPU.

